---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
export const prerender = true;
---
<Base title="What is ai.txt?" description="Learn about ai.txt — the emerging standard for declaring AI usage policies. Experimental spec, format guide, and best practices.">
  <article class="learn-page">
    <div class="container content">
      <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a> / <a href="/learn/ai-txt">Learn</a> / <span>ai.txt</span>
      </nav>

      <h1>What is ai.txt? <span class="badge experimental">Experimental</span></h1>
      <p class="lead">
        <strong>ai.txt</strong> is an emerging proposal for declaring your website's AI usage policies.
        While robots.txt controls <em>access</em>, ai.txt communicates <em>intent</em> — how you want
        AI companies to use (or not use) your content.
      </p>

      <div class="notice">
        <strong>Note:</strong> ai.txt is not yet a widely adopted standard. It's an experimental
        proposal being explored by the web community. We track it because it represents an
        important trend toward explicit AI content governance.
      </div>

      <section>
        <h2>Why ai.txt?</h2>
        <p>
          robots.txt can block crawlers, but it can't express nuance like:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>"You can use our content for search results but not for training"</li>
          <li>"You must attribute us when using our content"</li>
          <li>"We consent to AI usage of our public documentation but not user-generated content"</li>
        </ul>
        <p>ai.txt fills this gap with a simple, human-readable policy file.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>The Format</h2>
        <p>Place a file at <code>/ai.txt</code> on your domain root. The format uses simple key-value pairs:</p>
        <pre><code># AI Policy for example.com

Policy: Allow training on public documentation
Policy: Require attribution for generated content
Policy: Disallow training on user-generated content
Contact: ai-policy@example.com
Preferred-Model-Use: search, summarization
Disallowed-Model-Use: training, fine-tuning
License: CC-BY-4.0</code></pre>

        <h3>Common fields</h3>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Field</th><th>Description</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>Policy</code></td><td>A human-readable policy statement (can appear multiple times)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>Contact</code></td><td>Email or URL for AI usage inquiries</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>Preferred-Model-Use</code></td><td>Comma-separated list of acceptable AI uses</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>Disallowed-Model-Use</code></td><td>Comma-separated list of prohibited AI uses</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>License</code></td><td>SPDX license identifier for AI usage</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Best Practices</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Be specific about what you allow and disallow — vague policies are hard to enforce.</li>
          <li>Include a contact email so AI companies can reach you with questions.</li>
          <li>Reference your Terms of Service or a dedicated AI policy page.</li>
          <li>Update your ai.txt when your policies change.</li>
          <li>Use ai.txt alongside robots.txt, not as a replacement — they serve different purposes.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>How It Relates to Other Files</h2>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>File</th><th>Controls</th><th>Enforcement</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>robots.txt</strong></td><td>Crawler access (allow/block paths)</td><td>Technical (bots check it)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>ai.txt</strong></td><td>Usage policy (how content may be used)</td><td>Legal/social (policy declaration)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>llms.txt</strong></td><td>Content structure (what the site is about)</td><td>Informational (helps AI understand)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>
          Think of it this way: robots.txt is the <strong>lock on your door</strong>.
          ai.txt is the <strong>terms of the lease</strong>.
          llms.txt is the <strong>welcome packet</strong>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <div class="cta-box">
        <h3>Check your site's AI policy</h3>
        <p>See if you have an ai.txt and how it compares.</p>
        <a href="/" class="action-btn action-btn-primary">Scan your domain</a>
        <a href="/tools/generator/ai-txt" class="action-btn action-btn-secondary">Generate ai.txt</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .learn-page { padding: var(--space-8) 0 var(--space-16); }
  .content { max-width: var(--content-width); }
  .breadcrumb { font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-bottom: var(--space-6); }
  .breadcrumb a { color: var(--color-text-secondary); }

  h1 { font-size: var(--text-3xl); font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: var(--space-4); display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--space-3); flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .lead { font-size: var(--text-lg); color: var(--color-text-secondary); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed); margin-bottom: var(--space-8); }

  .badge { font-size: var(--text-xs); font-weight: 600; padding: 2px 8px; border-radius: var(--radius-full); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; }
  .experimental { background: #fef3c7; color: #92400e; }

  .notice { background: #fef3c7; border: 1px solid #fbbf24; border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4); margin-bottom: var(--space-8); font-size: var(--text-sm); }

  h2 { font-size: var(--text-xl); font-weight: 600; margin-top: var(--space-10); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); }
  h3 { font-size: var(--text-lg); font-weight: 600; margin-top: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-3); }

  section { margin-bottom: var(--space-8); }
  ul, ol { padding-left: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); }
  li { margin-bottom: var(--space-2); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed); }

  code { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.9em; background: var(--color-bg); padding: 1px 4px; border-radius: var(--radius-sm); }
  pre { background: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4); overflow-x: auto; margin: var(--space-4) 0; }
  pre code { background: none; padding: 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); line-height: 1.6; }

  table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: var(--space-4) 0; }
  th, td { padding: var(--space-3); text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border); }
  th { font-weight: 600; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-text-secondary); }
  td { font-size: var(--text-sm); }

  .cta-box {
    margin-top: var(--space-12); padding: var(--space-8); background: var(--color-primary-light);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg); text-align: center;
  }
  .cta-box h3 { margin-top: 0; }
  .cta-box p { color: var(--color-text-secondary); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); }
  .cta-box :global(.action-btn) { margin: 0 var(--space-2); display: inline-block; }
  :global(.action-btn) { padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-6); border-radius: var(--radius-md); font-size: var(--text-sm); font-weight: 600; font-family: var(--font-sans); cursor: pointer; text-decoration: none; border: none; transition: background 0.15s; }
  :global(.action-btn-primary) { background: var(--color-primary); color: white; }
  :global(.action-btn-primary:hover) { background: var(--color-primary-hover); text-decoration: none; }
  :global(.action-btn-secondary) { background: var(--color-surface); color: var(--color-text); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); }
  :global(.action-btn-secondary:hover) { background: var(--color-bg); }
</style>
